Cyril Ramaphosa has been elected president of the African National Congress (ANC) at the ruling party’s 54th National Elective Conference at the Nasrec Expo Centre in Johannesburg. Matamela Cyril Ramaphosa was born on 17 November 1952 in Soweto, Johannesburg, the second of three children. Before being elected as Secretary General of the ANC in 1991, Ramaphosa became head of the ANC team in negotiating the end of apartheid with the National Party government. After the first democratic elections in 1994, Ramaphosa became a member of Parliament and was elected chairperson of its Constitutional Assembly, playing a central role in the government of national unity. After losing the presidential race to Thabo Mbeki in 1997, Ramaphosa resigned from his political career and moved into the private sector where he became a director at New Africa Investments Limited. While there was speculation that Ramaphosa would return to politics in 2007, before the 2009 South African presidential election, he said he was not interested In May 2012, however, he was asked to run for the ANC presidency again and threw his hat into the ring, becoming a candidate for the deputy presidency with the strong backing of the Zuma camp. He was elected deputy president of the ANC in December 2012, beating Phosa and Tokyo Sexwale. In 2017 Ramaphosa started the CR17 campaign as a platform for his presidential campaign ahead of the elective conference. -TNA Reporter  